We recommend that the Local Chief Executive:

a.	Instruct the Municipal Human Resource Management Officer to:
i.	strengthen the internal control system in hiring of additional workforce through job/order/contract of service.   Limit the hiring of JOs per Office or to the actual number needed for normal operations, taking into consideration the volume of transactions per Office;


ii.	instruct the JO employees to include quantifiable date in their accomplishment report such as number of tasks completed, clients served, documents processed, inspections conducted, reports prepared, or any other relevant performance;

b.	Direct all JO employees to quantify all the accomplishments in the accomplishment reports;

c.	Direct the Acting Municipal Treasurer to liquidate the cash advances for payment of JO services within five (5) days after each fifteen (15)-day or end-of-month pay period; and

d.	Direct the Municipal Accountant - Designate to ensure the validity and propriety of the supporting documents attached to the payroll.

We recommended and management agreed that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant – Designate to:
enforce the immediate liquidation of the unliquidated cash advances;
send demand letters to the employees concerned to liquidate/settle the long outstanding cash advances especially the above-mentioned prepayments for travel and those granted to former SDOs;
withhold the salaries of the accountable officers who are still connected with the Municipality, and should not defer the liquidation of their cash advances at their retirement;
refrain from granting cash advance to the Municipal Treasurer and other municipal officials and employees unless the previous cash advance given to them is first settled or a proper accounting thereof is made; and
assign a staff to monitor closely the liquidation of these outstanding cash advances.
The Municipal Accountant-Designate submitted a ledger to the Audit Team, reflecting the adjustments made to correct the misclassified accounts.  In response, the municipal officials concerned agreed to implement the audit recommendations and committed to exerting efforts to liquidate the long-outstanding cash advances.

We recommended and management agreed that the Municipal Mayor require the:
a. 	Municipal Accountant - Designate to:

i.	Maintain and regularly update the Property Ledger and Subsidiary Ledgers, and indicate complete information of PPE;
ii.	Prepare a Depreciation Lapsing Schedule and compute the monthly depreciation expense consistent with existing rules and regulations;
iii.	Prepare a journal entry voucher to reclassify the PPE totaling ₱20,891,264.64 to their appropriate accounts;
iv.	Be guided with the descriptions of the accounts provided under COA Circular No. 2015-009, so that the appropriate accounts will be used for each completed infrastructure project, and prevent the misstatement of PPE accounts.

b. 	Acting Municipal Treasurer to:

i.	Submit to the Audit Team a copy of the RPCPPE for CY 2024 and subsequent years on time;
ii.	Be mindful of the due dates and reports to be submitted to the Audit Team to avoid potential sanctions; and
iii.	Be attentive to official communications that require immediate compliance.

We also recommended that the Municipal Mayor create an Inventory Committee to be able to prepare and submit the physical inventory report every year-end.

